Quantitative Methods for Management (STA 511)

Unit 1: Foundations of Quantitative Methods [6 Hours]
1.1 Introduction to Quantitative Methods
Role of quantitative methods in business
Applications in risk and insurance management
Software tools for quantitative analysis
Overview of data-driven decision-making
Example of predicting claim frequencies

1.2 Data Types and Measurement Scales
Nominal, ordinal, interval, and ratio scales
Qualitative vs. quantitative data
Structured vs. unstructured data
Data quality issues (accuracy, completeness, consistency)

1.3 Descriptive Statistics
Measures of central tendency (mean, median, mode)
Measures of dispersion (variance, standard deviation, range)
Data visualization (histograms, box plots, scatter plots)
Practical exercise on claim amounts distribution
Skewness and Kurtosis

Unit 2: Probability and Risk Analysis [6 Hours]

2.1 Basics of Probability
Probability rules and theorems
Conditional probability
Bayesâ€™ theorem
Real-world examples in business and insurance

2.2 Probability Distributions
Discrete distributions (Binomial, Poisson)
Continuous distributions (Normal, Exponential)
Heavy-tailed distributions (Pareto)

2.3 Applications in Risk Management
Risk assessment using probability
Monte Carlo simulations for risk modeling

Unit 3: Statistical Inference [4 Hours]
3.1 Sampling and Estimation
Sampling methods (random, stratified, cluster)
Sampling bias
Point estimation
Confidence intervals

3.2 Hypothesis Testing
Null and alternative hypotheses
p-values
Significance levels
Applications in business and insurance

Unit 4: Introduction to Predictive Modeling [4 Hours]
4.1 Correlation and Regression Analysis
Correlation
Simple linear regression
Interpretation of regression outputs
Predictive modeling
Multicollinearity

4.2 Introduction to Time Series Analysis
Trend
Seasonality
Forecasting basics
Insurance premium forecasting
ARIMA models

Unit 5: Decision Analysis and Optimization Techniques [4 Hours]
5.1 Decision Analysis
Decision trees
Expected utility theory
Applications in underwriting and risk assessment
Sensitivity analysis

5.2 Optimization Techniques
Linear programming
Resource allocation
Portfolio management
Risk mitigation
